00:52:49.660 --> 00:52:52.150
or just getting stuff wrong.

00:52:52.150 --> 00:52:58.080
And so we're drawing heavily off
of childhood religious history,

00:52:58.080 --> 00:53:00.480
and current experience,
and also the notion

00:53:00.480 --> 00:53:03.280
that this is a sort of
enormous sprawling bureaucracy,

00:53:03.280 --> 00:53:06.040
and many of the writers
who are on the team

00:53:06.040 --> 00:53:09.060
have a lot of experience
in one or many of those.

00:53:09.060 --> 00:53:15.580
So often for me
trying to write stuff

00:53:15.580 --> 00:53:18.590
that I don't have direct
physical or personal experience

00:53:18.590 --> 00:53:21.230
with is a question of
I'm talking to as many

00:53:21.230 --> 00:53:24.860
people as I can, but then
trying to identify what

00:53:24.860 --> 00:53:28.630
in this system corresponds
with something that I do

00:53:28.630 --> 00:53:31.680
have direct physical
experience of.

00:53:31.680 --> 00:53:33.842
If there's some correspondence
that I can find,

00:53:33.842 --> 00:53:35.550
then it kind of breaks
open a little bit,

00:53:35.550 --> 00:53:37.495
and it becomes much
easier to navigate,

00:53:37.495 --> 00:53:39.620
but there's always the risk
of getting stuff wrong.

00:53:42.357 --> 00:53:43.940
LINDSAY SMITH: For
the "Witch" series,

00:53:43.940 --> 00:53:46.020
I think we focused
more on making things

00:53:46.020 --> 00:53:49.350
feel authentic than accurate.

00:53:49.350 --> 00:53:53.190
So what I mean by that is, as
the resident Russian scholar

00:53:53.190 --> 00:53:54.960
for the team, I
can kind of step in

00:53:54.960 --> 00:53:56.580
and say, I don't
really think they

00:53:56.580 --> 00:53:59.880
would make a big deal about
Christmas at this time of year.

00:53:59.880 --> 00:54:03.300
I don't think the KGB-- someone
would say this this directly.

00:54:03.300 --> 00:54:05.580
There would be a little
more subterfuge about it,

00:54:05.580 --> 00:54:07.340
but by the same
token, I can't exactly

00:54:07.340 --> 00:54:09.600
go over to Lubyanka,
the KGB headquarters,

00:54:09.600 --> 00:54:12.970
and read through their archives,
what hasn't been burned down

00:54:12.970 --> 00:54:15.970
in 1993.

00:54:15.970 --> 00:54:20.140
So we just try to strive to
hit the right cultural notes

00:54:20.140 --> 00:54:23.990
and make it the feel immersive
without being completely

00:54:23.990 --> 00:54:25.490
accurate, and
nobody in the story

00:54:25.490 --> 00:54:27.750
is necessarily going to
have all the answers either.

00:54:27.750 --> 00:54:29.750
People are only going to
be aware of their slice

00:54:29.750 --> 00:54:32.060
of the universe at
that time, and the same

00:54:32.060 --> 00:54:34.340
went for the witchcraft
elements, too.

00:54:34.340 --> 00:54:36.440
One of the other things
we did at the story summit

00:54:36.440 --> 00:54:38.965
was figure out how our magic
worked, and we tossed out

00:54:38.965 --> 00:54:40.840
a bunch of different
ideas, but we ultimately

00:54:40.840 --> 00:54:46.690
settled on a medieval elemental
type magic, a lot of chemical

00:54:46.690 --> 00:54:51.620
symbols, and use of
different elements including

00:54:51.620 --> 00:54:53.390
herbs, and grasses,
and minerals,

00:54:53.390 --> 00:54:55.050
and things of that sort.

00:54:55.050 --> 00:54:57.810
So once we laid
down that structure,

00:54:57.810 --> 00:54:59.890
even though our spells
probably don't really

00:54:59.890 --> 00:55:05.350
work out exactly internally,
logistically-wise, they still

00:55:05.350 --> 00:55:08.740
have the right feeling
of a cohesive universe

00:55:08.740 --> 00:55:11.570
for the spells, and so on.

00:55:11.570 --> 00:55:14.150
MAX SALTONSTALL: Now, you've
taken on a big amalgamation.

00:55:14.150 --> 00:55:16.775
ELLEN KUSHNER: You don't really
want me to answer that, do you?

00:55:16.775 --> 00:55:18.250
Or do you?

00:55:18.250 --> 00:55:20.670
The thing is that I
created the original city,

00:55:20.670 --> 00:55:23.330
and the reason I think that
Julian wanted me to do this

00:55:23.330 --> 00:55:27.310
as part of Serial Box was that
he said it's just a fun place

00:55:27.310 --> 00:55:29.570
to hang out.

00:55:29.570 --> 00:55:32.967
And one of things that's been
particularly fun for me-- well

00:55:32.967 --> 00:55:34.800
first of all, creating
it-- that it was sort

00:55:34.800 --> 00:55:39.210
of every city and culture that
I had read about and really

00:55:39.210 --> 00:55:41.670
enjoyed, and I got to mix
them all up in a big stew pot.

00:55:41.670 --> 00:55:46.540
So I had Elizabethan London, and
the Regency London of Georgette

00:55:46.540 --> 00:55:49.430
Heyer, and a whole lot
of 18th century Paris,

00:55:49.430 --> 00:55:52.390
"Liason Dangereuse,"
certain amount

00:55:52.390 --> 00:55:54.240
of Damon Runyon
for my low lives,

00:55:54.240 --> 00:55:56.460
and my own life in
the '80s in New York

00:55:56.460 --> 00:55:59.900
when it was a very dangerous,
and very edgy, and also very

00:55:59.900 --> 00:56:01.590
gay city.

00:56:01.590 --> 00:56:05.360
And I just put it all
together and had a good time,

00:56:05.360 --> 00:56:08.020
and I also am very
aware now since I'm

00:56:08.020 --> 00:56:11.030
a New Yorker how much
a city will change

00:56:11.030 --> 00:56:13.420
during your own
lifetime, but one

00:56:13.420 --> 00:56:15.130
of my complaints
about fantasy novels

00:56:15.130 --> 00:56:17.960
is people don't
understand that, if you're

00:56:17.960 --> 00:56:20.590
living in a particular
world, you're very conscious

00:56:20.590 --> 00:56:21.494
of its changes.

00:56:21.494 --> 00:56:23.410
I think if we all went
back to Ancient Greece,

00:56:23.410 --> 00:56:24.650
it would all look
the same to us,

00:56:24.650 --> 00:56:26.450
but you had-- I can't
remember who it was,

00:56:26.450 --> 00:56:28.760
but one of the Greeks
saying, ugh, it's

00:56:28.760 --> 00:56:31.506
not like it used to be, and
everything's terrible now.

00:56:31.506 --> 00:56:33.130
And so you've got to
assume that people

00:56:33.130 --> 00:56:35.360
are hypersensitive
to those changes.

00:56:35.360 --> 00:56:38.200
And so one of the things that
we're doing with "Tremontaine"

00:56:38.200 --> 00:56:42.330
is quite consciously
setting it at a time

00:56:42.330 --> 00:56:46.050
when some of the things
that happen in later books

00:56:46.050 --> 00:56:48.800
that everybody's read
aren't happening yet.

00:56:48.800 --> 00:56:51.880
It's the prelude to what's been
happening in "Swordspoint,"

00:56:51.880 --> 00:56:55.107
and that's been
really interesting,

00:56:55.107 --> 00:56:57.440
and then of course, everybody
brings their own strengths

00:56:57.440 --> 00:56:58.210
and interests.

00:56:58.210 --> 00:56:59.860
One of the things
that I remember

00:56:59.860 --> 00:57:01.710
after "Swordspoint" people said,
well there's no middle class.

00:57:01.710 --> 00:57:02.800
I'm like, yeah there is.

00:57:02.800 --> 00:57:04.650
Just my characters
aren't interested in it.

00:57:04.650 --> 00:57:07.100
So we added them
in a later book.

00:57:07.100 --> 00:57:10.000
I collaborated on one with
my wife, Delia Sherman,

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:15.190
and just as with New York City,
or Paris, or anywhere else

00:57:15.190 --> 00:57:17.400
you go, you're only going
to see certain parts of it,

00:57:17.400 --> 00:57:19.050
and you're only going to be
interested in certain parts

00:57:19.050 --> 00:57:19.550
of it.

00:57:19.550 --> 00:57:21.770
There are other parts we
just haven't been to yet,

00:57:21.770 --> 00:57:23.340
and that's really
what "Tremontaine"

00:57:23.340 --> 00:57:25.424
has been able to do with
our cast of writers.

00:57:25.424 --> 00:57:26.340
MAX SALTONSTALL: Cool.

00:57:26.340 --> 00:57:28.100
Well, thank you all very
much for joining us.

00:57:28.100 --> 00:57:29.620
I look forward to
the next episode.

00:57:29.620 --> 00:57:30.180
LINDSAY SMITH: Thank you.

00:57:30.180 --> 00:57:31.230
MAX GLADSTONE: Thank you.

00:57:31.230 --> 00:57:32.780
